    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-06-26T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-06-26T10:00:00-05:00" n="637"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d637">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/4198: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Casablanca</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Goold</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Casablanca</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-06-26T16:00:00+01:00"
                            >June 26, 1940—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 9 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>42. Referring to the Department’s telegram No. 21, June 24, 1 see no evidence of
                    the assumption of any initiative by any of the high officials looking to the
                    organization of resistance. They are the purest conventionalists who will
                    probably follow whatever orders they get, even to fighting for Hitler.<note
                        n="37" xml:id="d637fn37">Adolf Hitler, Chancellor of the German
                        Reich.</note> This applies to all services.</p>
                <p>Younger men are preparing to join the British. Some aviators will fly their
                    planes, and some naval commanders will take their ships to Gibraltar. Many of
                    the more spirited men in the Government at Rabat mean to go with Great Britain,
                    among them Marchal,<note n="38" xml:id="d637fn38">Léon Marchal, Director of
                        Commerce and Industry, French Residency General, Morocco.</note> I am sure
                    the Department will be glad to know.</p>
                <p>But these men are much concerned about their families against whom reprisals well
                    may be taken and anxiously inquire as to the possibilities of transit visas for
                    Canada.</p>
                <p>The truth of the armistice terms is carefully concealed from the public and the
                    press has assumed an unfriendly attitude to Great Britain. In short, the
                    spectacle is that of human nature at its worst, acting just as Hitler would have
                    it act.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Goold</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
